cks: A Model System for Investigating Conspecific Parasitism in Cavity-Nesting Birds -- t17. The Mexican Jay as a Model System for the Study of Large Group Size and Its Social Correlates in a Territorial Bird -- t18. Sexual Selection in the Barn Swallow -- tPART IV. Mammal Model Systems -- t19. Cunning Coyotes: Tireless Tricksters, Protean Predators -- t20. Bottlenose Dolphins: Social Relationships in a Big-Brained Aquatic Mammal -- t21. Bonnet Macaques: Evolutionary Perspectives on Females' Lives -- t22. Chimpanzee Hunters: Chaos or Cooperation in the Forest? -- t23. Cooperative Hunting and Sociality in African Wild Dogs, Lycaon pictus -- t24. Gorilla Socioecology: Conflict and Compromise between the Sexes -- t25. Cheetahs and Their Mating System -- tClosing Thoughts -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA key way that behavioral ecologists develop general theories of animal behavior is by studying one species or a closely related group of species--''model systems''--over a long period. This book brings together some of the field's most respected researchers to describe why they chose their systems, how they integrate theoretical, conceptual, and empirical work, lessons for the practice of the discipline, and potential avenues of future research. Their model systems encompass a wide range of animals and behavioral issues, from dung flies to sticklebacks, dolphins to African wild dogs, from foraging to aggression, territoriality to reproductive suppression. Model Systems in Behavioral Ecology offers an unprecedented ''systems'' focus and revealing insights into the confluence of personal curiosity and scientific inquiry. It will be an invaluable text for behavioral ecology courses and a helpful overview--and a preview of coming developments--for advanced researchers. The twenty-five chapters are divided into four sections: insects and arachnids, amphibians and reptiles, birds, and mammals. In addition to the editor, the contributors include Geoff A. Parker, Thomas D. Seeley, Naomi Pierce, Kern Reeve, Gerald S. Wilkinson, Bert Hölldobler and Flavio Roces, George W. Uetz, Michael J. Ryan and Gil Rosenthal, Judy Stamps, H. Carl Gerhardt, Barry Sinervo, Robert Warner, Manfred Milinski, David F. Westneat, Alan C. Kamil and Alan B. Bond, Paul Sherman, Jerram L. Brown, Anders Pape Møller, Marc Bekoff, Richard C. Connor, Joan B. Silk, Christopher Boesch, Scott Creel, A.H. Harcourt, and Tim Caro and M. J. Kelly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnimal behavior. 0aAnimal ecology. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biology.2bisacsh1 aBekoff, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoesch, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBond, Alan B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Jerram L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaro, T. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnor, Richard C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreel, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDugatkin, Lee Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDugatkin, Lee Alan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGerhardt, H. Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarcourt, A. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHölldobler, Bert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamil, Alan C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, M. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato